payload.user_prompt:
Propose 4 distinct strategies to beat the baseline.

PROBLEM: Euclidean TSP on the TSPLIB95 benchmark (known optima). The solver is run on several dev instances; score = mean gap %% above the known optimum (lower is better, 0 = optimal on every instance). Distances use the TSPLIB metric: each edge rounded to the nearest integer. The winning solver is re-evaluated on held-out instances at the end.
INSTANCE: TSPLIB95 dev set: berlin52 (52 cities), st70 (70 cities), eil76 (76 cities), kroA100 (100 cities), rd100 (100 cities). Optima are known; score is the mean gap %% above optimum across all dev instances (TSPLIB rounded-integer metric). 6 held-out instances are kept hidden for final verification.
SCOPE: {"objective": "Minimize the mean gap percentage above the known TSPLIB95 optima across 5 dev instances (berlin52, st70, eil76, kroA100, rd100) by improving upon the nearest-neighbor + 2-opt baseline score of 6.59%.", "success_criteria": {"target_improvement_pct": 18.0, "rationale": "An 18% improvement over the baseline 6.59% gap means achieving a mean gap of approximately 5.40% or lower. For instances of this size (52\u2013100 cities), well-implemented local search enhancements such as 3-opt, Lin-Kernighan style moves, or Or-opt are known to reliably close 50\u201380% of the gap above optimum within tight time budgets. The operator-suggested 18% improvement is realistic and attainable within 10s per experiment using stronger perturbation or move operators beyond basic 2-opt."}, "constraints": ["Maximum 5 optimization rounds allowed", "Total budget must not exceed $2 USD", "Each experiment must complete within 10 seconds of wall-clock time", "Distances must use the TSPLIB rounded-integer metric (nint) for correctness", "Solution must be a valid Hamiltonian tour (visit each city exactly once)", "Solver must generalize: no instance-specific hardcoding of routes or optima", "All 5 dev instances must be evaluated in each scored run"], "stop_conditions": ["Mean gap % reaches 5.40% or lower (18% improvement over baseline achieved)", "Mean gap % reaches 0.0% (all instances solved optimally)", "5 optimization rounds have been completed", "Budget of $2 USD is exhausted", "Further algorithmic changes produce no measurable improvement across two consecutive rounds"], "reasoning": "For Euclidean TSP instances in the 52\u2013100 city range, the nearest-neighbor + 2-opt combination typically yields gaps of 4\u201310% above optimum depending on instance structure. Stronger moves such as Or-opt (relocate single cities or chains), 3-opt, or Lin-Kernighan style moves can substantially reduce this gap within seconds for these small instance sizes. An 18% relative improvement (from 6.59% to ~5.40% mean gap) is conservative enough to be reliably achievable yet meaningful as a quality bar. The 10s time limit is generous for instances up to 100 cities, allowing iterated local search or repeated restarts with 3-opt, which commonly achieve sub-2% gaps on these benchmarks. The 5-round limit and $2 budget constrain exploration but are sufficient to implement and tune one or two algorithmic upgrades."}

Each strategy must be implementable in pure Python within the time limit.
Return JSON:
{
  "hypotheses": [
    {"name": "<short name>", "strategy": "<algorithm family>",
      "hypothesis": "<falsifiable claim: doing X will improve over baseline because Y>",
      "risk": "<main reason this could fail>"}
  ]
}

